<div class="description">
    <h3>Description</h3>

    <div class="body">
        <p>Currently when a Zend_Db_Table_Row object is created, its data is set by assigning explicit PHP values and then calling the save() method to INSERT/UPDATE the database record.</p>

<pre class="highlight"><code>
$row = $table-&gt;fetchNew();
$row-&gt;createDate = date('Y-m-d H:i:s');
$row-&gt;title = 'Awesome';
$row-&gt;save();
</code></pre>

<p>My problem with this is that you are restricted to storing, for example, the time as reported by the web server. If I wanted to store the time as reported by the DB server, I can no longer use Zend_Db_Table_Row.</p>

<p>A possible solution would be to reuse the Zend_Db_Expr object. Then the code would be written as follows:</p>

<pre class="highlight"><code>
$row = $table-&gt;fetchNew();
$row-&gt;createDate = new Zend_Db_Expr('NOW()');
$row-&gt;title = 'Awesome';
$row-&gt;save();
</code></pre>

